  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the US\n- Initial focus on financial reporting requirements\n- Limited scope and enforcement mechanisms\n\n2. International Developments\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Developed comprehensive recommendations for national governments\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- PATRIOT Act (2001) in the US\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Expanded investigative powers\n- Increased international cooperation\n\n4. Modern Regulatory Framework\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Stricter know-your-customer (KYC) regulations\n- Increased transparency in financial transactions\n- Broader coverage of financial institutions and sectors\n\n5. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency\n- Digital transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced cyber-related financial crime prevention\n\n6. Current Trends\n- Expanded beneficial ownership reporting\n- More sophisticated risk-based approaches\n- Greater international collaboration\n- Continuous refinement of legal frameworks\n\nThese developments reflect an ongoing commitment to combating financial crimes globally.",
